{{Infobox deity Japan | name = Nagashiraha no Kami | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | generation_name = | predecessor = | successor = | deity_type = [[Amatsukami]] | full_name = Nagashiraha no Kami | aliases = Nagashiraha no Mikoto, Amashiraha no Torinomikoto, Amashiraha no Kami, Ame no Shiraha no Kami, etc. | alternative_titles = | divine_rank = None | divine_roles = [[Weaving]] | father = [[Amewakahayahi no Mikoto]] | mother = | relatives = | spouse = | siblings = | children = | shrines = [[Ame no Shiraha Shrine]] and others | blessings = | texts = | related_clans = Kamomibe (神麻績連) }}
'''Nagashiraha no Kami''' (長白羽神) is a deity featured in the *{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺}}*, appearing in the story of the {{ill|Ame no Iwato|ja|岩戸隠れ}} (Heavenly Rock Cave). The deity was tasked by {{ill|Omohikane|ja|思兼神}} to grow flax and weave the blue sacred cloth known as "Aonigite." Nagashiraha no Kami is revered as the ancestral deity of the Kamomibe (神麻績部), who wove the "Aratama" (荒妙, hemp cloth) offered at {{ill|Kanmisokihata-dono Shrine|ja|神麻続機殿神社}} for {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮}}.
The name "Shiraha" (白羽, "white feather") for white garments is said to derive from Nagashiraha no Kami. This deity is considered a kinship god of {{ill|Amenofutodama no Mikoto|ja|天太玉命}} but does not appear in the main {{ill|Kojiki|ja|記紀}} or {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} myths. Also known as Ame no Shiraha no Kami (天白羽神), Nagashiraha no Kami is sometimes linked to the {{ill|Tenpaku Faith|ja|天白信仰}}.
The deity is enshrined as the principal god at {{ill|Ame no Shiraha Shrine|ja|天志良波神社}}, an {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式}} shrine located in the former {{ill|Kujigun|ja|久慈郡}}, {{ill|Hitachi Province|ja|常陸国}} (now {{ill|Hitachiota|ja|常陸太田市}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県}}).<ref>‘Shinto Encyclopedia’ (Rinsen Shoten)</ref>
